---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'SoftwareApplication',
  name: 'peek',
  description:
    'Open-source, local-first browser-session forensics for AI coding agents. Passively records a masked, authenticated session of your real browser to a local SQLite store and exposes it — DOM history, console/network errors, and the action right before an error — to your agent over MCP, then turns it into a runnable Playwright repro the agent can re-run to verify its own fix. Ships as a Chrome MV3 extension, a stdio MCP server, and a CLI.',
  applicationCategory: 'DeveloperApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'macOS, Linux, Windows',
  softwareVersion: 'alpha',
  releaseNotes:
    'Pre-1.0 alpha; APIs may shift before 1.0. The Chrome extension is available on the Chrome Web Store.',
  license: 'https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0',
  url: 'https://peek.cubenest.in',
  offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
  isAccessibleForFree: true,
  sameAs: [
    'https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack',
    'https://www.npmjs.com/package/@peekdev/mcp',
    'https://www.npmjs.com/package/@peekdev/cli',
  ],
};
---

<Layout
  title="peek — let your AI coding agent debug what already happened in your real browser"
  description="peek records a masked browser session locally and turns it into a Playwright repro your AI agent can re-run over MCP. Local-first, redacted by default, no cloud."
>
  <h1>peek</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Let your AI coding agent debug what already happened in your real browser &mdash; peek turns your locally-recorded sessions (DOM history, console &amp; network errors, the action right before a failure) into a runnable Playwright repro it can re-run to verify its own fix.</p>

  <div class="badges">
    <span class="badge">Apache 2.0</span>
    <span class="badge">alpha</span>
    <span class="badge">local-first</span>
    <span class="badge">redacted by default</span>
    <span class="badge">MCP</span>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>peek</strong> records your real, authenticated browser session
    locally, then turns it into a runnable <strong>Playwright repro</strong> your
    AI coding agent can replay. Instead of guessing from a description of what
    broke, the agent re-runs the actual failure and checks whether its fix worked.
    It also queries the session&apos;s console, network, and DOM over
    <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io" rel="noopener">MCP</a> &mdash; so
    it&apos;s a Chrome extension + a stdio MCP server + a small CLI, for clients
    like <strong>Claude Code</strong>, <strong>Cursor</strong>,
    <strong>Cline</strong>, and <strong>Windsurf</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Everything stays on your machine, <strong>redacted by default</strong>: auth
    and cookie headers are deny-listed, and form values + PII are masked in the
    page before anything leaves the tab. No telemetry, no remote endpoints, no
    third-party SDKs &mdash; the browser talks to the local host over Chrome
    native messaging (stdio), and the database lives at <code>~/.peek/sessions.db</code>.
  </p>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="cta" href="/getting-started">Getting started &rarr;</a>
    <a class="cta secondary" href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/tree/main/packages/peek-mcp" rel="noopener">View on GitHub</a>
  </div>

  <h2>What it does</h2>
  <div class="feature-grid">
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>What happened before the error</h3>
      <p><code>get_user_action_before_error</code> assembles the causal chain &mdash; the clicks, DOM mutations, and network/console errors right before a failure &mdash; into one timeline with a narrative. With <code>query_dom_history</code>, <code>get_session_console_errors</code>, and <code>get_session_network_errors</code>, your agent debugs what already happened instead of guessing from a description.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Forensic read tools for agents</h3>
      <p><code>list_recent_sessions</code> / <code>get_session_summary</code> to orient, <code>get_dom_snapshot</code> / <code>query_dom_history</code> to inspect the DOM as it was at any moment, and <code>get_page_view</code> / <code>get_element_detail</code> for the live page. All over standard MCP &mdash; works with any MCP-aware client.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Replayable Playwright repro</h3>
      <p><code>generate_playwright_repro</code> turns a recorded session &mdash; the actual clicks, console, and network &mdash; into a runnable Playwright test. The agent re-runs it to verify a fix actually worked, and can seed a console-error-absence assertion so the bug can&apos;t silently come back.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Per-site, opt-in capture</h3>
      <p>No <code>&lt;all_urls&gt;</code> permission. You enable peek per origin in the side panel; it records nothing until you do.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Five-level permission model</h3>
      <p>From Level 1 (read-only, default) to Level 4 (Auto) &mdash; per origin. Destructive actions always prompt, even at Auto.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Local SQLite store</h3>
      <p>Sessions, console events, network metadata, and a tamper-evident audit log live in <code>~/.peek/sessions.db</code>. Delete or export with the <code>peek</code> CLI.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Redacted by default</h3>
      <p>Auth and cookie headers are deny-listed; form values and PII (cards, SSNs, JWTs, emails) are masked in the page before anything leaves the tab. Response bodies aren&apos;t captured unless you opt a single origin into Deep capture (off by default) &mdash; and even then they&apos;re masked and capped at 256&nbsp;KB. Apache-2.0, so you can audit the masking yourself.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature">
      <h3>Level-3 write tools (opt-in)</h3>
      <p><code>execute_action</code> and <code>request_authorization</code> let an agent take one-shot UI actions &mdash; gated by per-action user confirmation in the side panel.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Packages</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>@peekdev/mcp</code> &mdash; the native host + stdio MCP server. <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@peekdev/mcp" rel="noopener">npm</a></li>
    <li><code>@peekdev/cli</code> &mdash; <code>peek init</code>, <code>peek status</code>, sessions list/show/export/delete, audit log. <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@peekdev/cli" rel="noopener">npm</a></li>
    <li><code>@peekdev/extension</code> &mdash; the Chrome MV3 extension, <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/peek/dmgpmkeneheenpdnfmpjjahnkknkaejb" rel="noopener">available on the Chrome Web Store</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Privacy</h2>
  <p>
    peek is local-first by design. Nothing leaves your machine. The full
    data-handling policy is on <a href="/privacy">the privacy page</a> &mdash; it
    is also the canonical policy used for the Chrome Web Store listing.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Alpha note.</strong> peek is pre-1.0 &mdash; APIs may shift before 1.0.
    The Chrome extension is <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/peek/dmgpmkeneheenpdnfmpjjahnkknkaejb" rel="noopener">on the Chrome Web Store</a>;
    you can also load it unpacked for development (see
    <a href="/getting-started">Getting started</a>).
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
    Repository: <a href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack" rel="noopener">github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack</a>.
  </p>

  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
</Layout>
